===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|day}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|dæġ||day}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*dagaz||day}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-||to burn}}. Cognate with {{etyl|stq|-}} {{m|stq|Dai||day}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|dei||day}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|dag||day}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{m|nds|Dag||day}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Tag||day}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} and {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|sv|dag||day}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{m|is|dagur||day}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sq|-}} {{m|sq|djeg||to burn}}, {{etyl|lt|-}} {{m|lt|degti||to burn}}, {{etyl|xto|-}} {{m|xto|tsäk-}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{m|ru|жечь}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{m|sa|दाह||heat|tr=dāha|sc=Deva}}, {{m|sa|दहति||to burn|tr=dahati|sc=Deva}}.

{{etyl|la|-}} {{m|la|diēs}} is a [[false cognate]]; it derives from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*dyew-||to shine}}. The Latin Deus is the true cognate. As noctum is the root of nacht.

